      "id": "0fec8e80b2e2dce1",
      "text": "Apotaxis means escape from the world as a way of order. We prefer this term here because it carries less negative connotations and seems to be broad enough to encompass the way of the world as the production of the world. For a phasing of the evolution of religion with the help of the term [[Weltflucht]], see Bellah 1973: 284ff."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4da13f460cd22dfc",
      "text": "The thesis, which results from these abstract considerations, is in a preliminary formulation: Apotaxis (flight from the world) is a highly presuppositional event, which produces by itself, against which it profiles itself. The preference gradient in the direction of transcendence repels 'world', which precisely in the movement of flight condenses again and with ever more intensive flight encrusts ever more decisively."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cbfde41ca2455aff",
      "text": "The discussion of the basal paradox and its apotactic effect necessitated the use of the concept of \"world\". This term has been used in a preliminary, very fuzzy form that relies on intuitive understanding, but in such generality it cannot push the analysis further. The question of what 'world' means in the context of and in contact with the material we encounter as the semantic sediment of apotaxis can be answered relatively easily: the world one flees is the world of people. The 'flee the people!' is the central determinant of apotaxis (Heussi 1936: 244ff). It also unmistakably characterizes the approach to the New Testament foundation documents, in which the call to leave the world is understood, for the sake of imitatio, as a call to detachment from all human bonds."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4a01f0748d623239",
      "text": "Thus, in the end, there is a strange oscillation between flight from and conquest of the world (Stark 1967: 264). We can apply these considerations to the question of the system reference in which the argument is made. Apotaxis appears from the observer's perspective as flight from society, with which the observer assumes his world as the only real and relevant one; from the perspective of the observed system (if we consult its self-description), the anachoret, the monk, the religious conquers the actual world, and thus the inversion occurs: that the world-fugitive assumes the world-man to be world-fugitive, and that means: flight from God. Rituals of the complete renunciation of the world (Moorhouse 1969: 294) are then also, as one could show, rituals of the complete absorption into the real and actual, into the world actually intended by the metaphysical instance."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e719a7f065204f41",
      "text": "If apotaxis can be chalked up as an effect of paradox, and if one wants to see which structures of a social nature begin to condense around this effect, one observes in the early Christian communities an \"irrevocable structural tension\" (Bergmann 1985: 33; Schlissker 1951; Savramis 1962; Blazovich 1954) between the community ascetics and the strictly hierarchically organized community. The ascetics, who as psychic systems keep the initial situation of religion virulent, so to speak, and continuously feed it into the communication of the community system, constantly living the relatedness to transcendence against fixed system structures, differentiate themselves against the community, also move locally to its periphery (Bergmann 1985: 33), and more or less loosely unite."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a254aa3322b560a9",
      "text": "If it is true that the paradox resulting from the discussed code immanence/transcendence releases apotaxis from itself, which accumulates non-preferential world in the movement of escape, if it is further true, that a part of the apotactic movements is built into the universal church with the function of latent protection due to and with the help of rules, and that it can fulfill this function by ongoing regeneration of otherworldliness, if this is true in a debatable meaning, then the question arises how the paradox effects occur in the orders themselves and how they are managed or not managed there."
    },
