      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "57de914be8989118",
        "text": "This study attempts a theoretical approach to the phenomenon of the monks' flight from the world. A brief review of previous attempts shows the need for a broader theoretical orientation. Apotaxis (= world escape) is described as the effect of a paradox created by the code of the religious system (immanence/transcendence). The central thesis is that the religious world-flight of early Christianity produces systems (orders) that can fulfill the function of latent protection in the church. Silence is conceived as the reinforcement of apotaxis. The structure of the Carthusian order is sketched as an example of a system whose function is to guarantee the purity of church and order despite their worldliness."
